<subSubSection pageId="10" pageNumber="83" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph pageId="10" pageNumber="83">Diagnosis.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="10" pageNumber="83">Recognized by the following set of characters: dorsum with a mottled, dark brownish yellow coloration (Fig. 6); pronotal collar indistinct; femora entirely blackish, except for pale yellow annulation at basal one third of mesofemur.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="10" pageNumber="83">
Most similar to 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Miridae" genus="Xenocylapidius" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Xenocylapidius acutipennis" order="Hemiptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="83" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="acutipennis">Xenocylapidius acutipennis</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Miridae" genus="Xenocylapidius" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Xenocylapidius bioculatus" order="Hemiptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="83" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="bioculatus">Xenocylapidius bioculatus</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Miridae" genus="Xenocylapidius" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Xenocylapidius gemellus" order="Hemiptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="83" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="gemellus">Xenocylapidius gemellus</taxonomicName>
, and 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Miridae" genus="Xenocylapidius" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Xenocylapidius tamasi" order="Hemiptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="83" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="tamasi">Xenocylapidius tamasi</taxonomicName>
in sharing mottled dorsal coloration (Figs 1, 4, 5-6, 8). 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Miridae" genus="Xenocylapidius" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Xenocylapidius gressitti" order="Hemiptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="83" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="gressitti">Xenocylapidius gressitti</taxonomicName>
can, however, be distinguished by the coloration of femora.
</paragraph>
